.TH "WEAKMAP.DELETE" "3JS" "September 22, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
WeakMap.delete \- WeakMap.prototype.delete()
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]delete()\f[B]\f[R] method of \f[CR]WeakMap\f[R] instances
removes the entry specified by the key from this \f[CR]WeakMap\f[R].
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] weakmap = \f[B]new\f[R] WeakMap();
\f[B]const\f[R] object = {};

weakmap.set(object, 42);

console.log(weakmap.delete(object));
\f[I]// Expected output: true\f[R]

console.log(weakmap.has(object));
\f[I]// Expected output: false\f[R]
.EE
.SH SYNTAX
.IP
.EX
weakMapInstance.delete(key)
.EE
.SS Parameters
.TP
\f[B]key\f[R]
The key of the entry to remove from the \f[CR]WeakMap\f[R] object.
Object keys are compared by reference, not by value.
.SS Return value
\f[CR]true\f[R] if an entry in the \f[CR]WeakMap\f[R] object has been
removed successfully.
\f[CR]false\f[R] if the key is not found in the \f[CR]WeakMap\f[R].
Always returns \f[CR]false\f[R] if \f[CR]key\f[R] is not an object or a
non\-registered symbol.
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Using delete()
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] wm = \f[B]new\f[R] WeakMap();
wm.set(window, \(dqfoo\(dq);

wm.delete(window); \f[I]// Returns true. Successfully removed.\f[R]

wm.has(window); \f[I]// Returns false. The window object is no longer in the WeakMap.\f[R]
.EE
